SharePoint SE changed the Document Set rendering path. Microsoft confirms that previous SharePoint Server versions only supported classic UX for Document Sets, while SharePoint SE introduced modern Document Set support. The affected libraries rely on Nintex Forms attached to multiple content types, including Document Set-related content types. Nintex Forms can customise document and Document Set forms, but it depends on SharePoint routing the user to the correct content type form.

In SharePoint SE Modern libraries, actions such as New, Upload, Details pane, Edit properties and Document Set navigation do not always follow the same classic NewForm/EditForm/DisplayForm path used in SharePoint 2019. This creates a routing mismatch where Nintex may not load, may load against the wrong content type, or may be bypassed by the modern metadata panel. Switching the library to Classic restores the older SharePoint form-routing path, which is why the workaround is effective.

This same challenge is likely to apply to any migrated site or library that uses Document Sets, especially where Document Sets are combined with multiple content types, required metadata, custom forms or Nintex Forms. These sites should be treated as exception cases and checked individually rather than assuming the SharePoint 2019 behaviour will carry across to SharePoint SE Modern experience.

For Prop, we have changed the affected library back to Classic experience. This is not a perfect outcome, as it means the library does not use the newer Modern interface, but it does restore the functional path needed for users to work with Document Sets, content types and Nintex Forms. At this stage, Classic experience is the practical workaround for affected libraries where the business function is more important than retaining the Modern user interface.
